			<div id="content"><div id="wsite-content" class="wsite-elements wsite-not-footer">
	<h2 class="wsite-content-title" style="text-align:left;"><span style="color:rgb(255, 255, 255); font-weight:400"><em><font size="6">Ancient Cities of the Emirates</font></em></span><br/><br/></h2>

<div><div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style="padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:left">
<a>
<img src="/web/20171026111746im_/http://www.beyonddubai.net/uploads/2/9/1/0/29102015/1102785.jpg?706" alt="Picture" style="width:auto;max-width:100%"/>
</a>
<div style="display:block;font-size:90%"></div>
</div></div>

<div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;"><span style="text-decoration:none; font-style:normal; font-weight:400; color:rgb(231, 231, 231); "><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><font size="3"><font size="4">If you think the Emirates is just shopping malls and beaches, Lambos and limos, bling and pizzazz,&nbsp;you couldn't be more wrong. It is also&nbsp;the site&nbsp;of many of the greatest lost cities of Arabia, the home of ancient civilizations, easily on a par with better-known lost cities such as Ubar, aka Iram of the Pillars or the "Atlantis of the Sands", rediscovered in southern Oman in the 1990s. Here's a quick guide to the UAE's own ancient&nbsp;"lost cities", in rough order of driving distance from Dubai.<br/><br/><font size="5"><strong>Mleiha</strong><br/></font>Less than an hour's drive&nbsp;from Dubai&nbsp;along the&nbsp;Sharjah-Kalba road, Mleiha in its heyday at around the time of Christ was one of the most substantial ancient settlements in the Emirates&mdash;a city a mile wide with&nbsp;hundreds of&nbsp;houses and metal-working sites, continuously inhabited for over 500 years from the mid Iron Age until the 1st century AD&mdash;when it was abandoned and forgotten for almost two thousand years.<br/><br/>Its large square fort, about 200 feet&nbsp;along each side,&nbsp;is its most significant feature and is&nbsp;today housed under a huge metal hangar just south of the modern village of Mleiha about 45 minutes south-east of Dubai on the road towards Hatta.&nbsp;<br/><br/>Excavations have revealed two iron-foundries, producing both weapons and coins, protected by the fort and surrounded by many houses, indicating that a significant number of people lived and worked there. This was an industrial complex, the Detroit of its day. Iron ingots and finished products were&nbsp;transported from Mleiha to the coast at Ad-Dur, from where they were shipped up the Arabian Gulf to customers in Mesopotamia and the Levant.</font><br/></font></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></div>

<div><div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-thin " style="padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0px;margin-right:0px;text-align:left">
<a>
<img src="/web/20171026111746im_/http://www.beyonddubai.net/uploads/2/9/1/0/29102015/millar06-mleiha-tomb-small_orig.jpg" alt="Picture" style="width:auto;max-width:100%"/>
</a>
<div style="display:block;font-size:90%">Umm al-Nar period communal tomb dated to around 2500 BC is one of the highlights of the Mleiha site, about an hour’s drive from Dubai. Image credit: Government of Sharjah</div>
</div></div>

<div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;"><span style="text-decoration:none; font-style:normal; font-weight:400; color:rgb(231, 231, 231); "><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><strong><br/><font size="4"><font size="5">Ad-Dur</font><br/></font></strong><font size="4">Ad-Dur&nbsp;was&nbsp;the largest lost city of the UAE in terms of sheer size and one of the most significant lost cities of Arabia, and&nbsp;is roughly contemporary with Mleiha. The archaeological site itself is huge and spreads over several square miles and is almost as big as the modern city of Umm al-Quwain,&nbsp;just outside of&nbsp;which it&nbsp;is located, along the coast between Sharjah and Ras al Khaimah. <br/><br/>It flourished between 200 BC and 300 AD and is very likely the major trading centre known to Pliny as 'Omana', the primary port through which iron, weapons and other goods from Mleiha were exported, and imports came from as far afield as China, India and Iran. By all accounts it was the early Christian era equivalent of Rotterdam. A contemporary Greek description lists exports from Ad-Dur as including pearls, purple dye, clothing, wine, gold and slaves, and a great quantity of dates. <br/><br/>The name Ad-Dur means simply 'the houses', which is apparently how the area was known for generations thanks to the ghostly outlines of houses scattered&nbsp;across the area,&nbsp;together with a fort, a temple and graves interspersed between them. Although its existence was therefore known to locals for generations,&nbsp;archaeologists only heard about it and rediscovered it in the 1970s. In keeping with its status as a true lost city of the UAE there are no signs pointing to Ad-Dur today, and even when you know exactly where to look its easy to miss.&nbsp;</font><br/></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></div>

<div><div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-thin " style="padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:left">
<a>
<img src="/web/20171026111746im_/http://www.beyonddubai.net/uploads/2/9/1/0/29102015/2831798.jpg?690" alt="Picture" style="width:690;max-width:100%"/>
</a>
<div style="display:block;font-size:90%">Ad-Dur, hard to find...</div>
</div></div>

<div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;"><span style="text-decoration:none; font-style:normal; font-weight:400; color:rgb(231, 231, 231); "><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><strong><br/><font size="4"><font size="5">Tell Abraq</font><br/></font></strong><font size="3"><font size="4">One of the easiest&nbsp;of the lost cities&nbsp;to visit, Tell Abraq is just outside Umm al-Quwain right next to the main coastal road to Ras al-Khaimah where it joins with the E55 towards Dhaid. As you turn onto the E55 you see&nbsp;the large brown heritage sign&nbsp;on your right. <br/><br/>Tell Abraq&nbsp;is unusual because&nbsp;of its incredibly long history&mdash;it&nbsp;was continuously occupied for around two thousand years from 2500 BC until 500 BC. When originally constructed Tell Abraq was on the coast (today it is about&nbsp;two miles inland), and its main feature is a massive stone&nbsp;fort about&nbsp;two hundred feet in diameter with a communal tomb containing the remains of around 300 people.&nbsp;The fort itself is the largest Bronze Age building anywhere on the Arabian Peninsula.<br/><br/>Artifacts found there come from as far afield as Bahrain, Iran, Afghanistan and Uzbekistan, so it is clear that it was a major trading hub. But it was also&nbsp;a major manufacturing site for bronze goods,&nbsp;using copper&nbsp;from the mysterious 'Land of Magan' copper mining area in the Hajar Mountains just to the south&nbsp;around the present-day UAE/Oman border area.<br/><br/>Tell Abraq has been extensively excavated and has taught us much of what we know about Bronze Age life in the Emirates, many of the finds now being in the magnificent Sharjah Museum.</font><br/></font></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></div>

<div><div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-thin " style="padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:left">
<a>
<img src="/web/20171026111746im_/http://www.beyonddubai.net/uploads/2/9/1/0/29102015/6316256.jpg?670" alt="Picture" style="width:670;max-width:100%"/>
</a>
<div style="display:block;font-size:90%">Tell Abraq, the site of 2000 years of continuous settlement</div>
</div></div>

<div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;"><span style="text-decoration:none; font-style:normal; font-weight:400; color:rgb(231, 231, 231); "><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><br/><font size="3"><font size="4"><strong><font size="5">Jazirat al-Hamra</font><br/></strong>Most lost cities are lost in space, but Jazirat al-Hamra is lost in time. Originally a small fishing village just outside of Ras al-Khaimah, it was abandoned in the 1960s&mdash;its inhabitants simply walked away, drawn to Abu Dhabi by the oil industry. But the original owners still own their houses and won't let the area be redeveloped, so the buildings&nbsp;sit there, quietly crumbling, while Ras al-Khaimah develops around them. What remains is quite substantial and includes several hundred houses, two small forts, three mosques, several nice wind-towers, a street full of empty shops, and what looks like several schools and community halls.<br/><br/>Despite being relatively recent it is a fascinating place to wander around and gives a great insight into how houses were traditionally constructed in the Emirates, and in fact is described on the Ras al-Khaimah tourism website as 'the last authentic and traditional town left in the UAE'.</font><br/></font></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></div>

<div><div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-thin " style="padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:left">
<a>
<img src="/web/20171026111746im_/http://www.beyonddubai.net/uploads/2/9/1/0/29102015/9794119.jpg?709" alt="Picture" style="width:709;max-width:100%"/>
</a>
<div style="display:block;font-size:90%">Jazirat al-Hamra, a 'lost city' in the true sense</div>
</div></div>

<div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;"><span style="text-decoration:none; font-style:normal; font-weight:400; color:rgb(231, 231, 231); "><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><br/><font size="3"><font size="4"><strong><font size="5">Julfar</font></strong><br/>Julfar is perhaps the most famous of all the lost cities of Arabia, a port just north of present-day Ras al-Khaimah that in its heyday in the 10th to 14th centuries AD&nbsp;was a larger and more important city than London and a truly global trading hub, a centre from which Arab merchants routinely made mammoth 18 month sea&nbsp;voyages&nbsp;to China and traded everything imaginable&mdash;but then disappeared so completely&nbsp;that its very location was forgotten for 300 years.<br/><br/>Flourishing&nbsp;during the golden age of long-distance Arab trading and seafaring, Julfar's most famous inhabitant was Ahmed ibn Majid, probably the most famous Arab sailor and navigator of all time.&nbsp;At that time the Arab world was far ahead of Europe&nbsp;in terms of navigation and seamanship, as ibn Majid himself wrote: 'They cannot understand the way we navigate,&nbsp;but we understand the way they do. We possess scientific books that give stellar altitudes...but they have no science and no books, only the compass and dead-reckoning. We can easily sail in their ships and upon their sea, so they have great respect for us and look up to us."&nbsp;A comparable situation today might be the technological superiority that the US and Europe have in&nbsp;planetary exploration over most other nations.<br/><br/>Ibn Majid was not unique in his expertise in navigation but he was unique in writing it down, notably in his thoughtfully titled Book of Useful Information in which he describes the history and principles of navigation, the proper use of rhumb lines and lunar mansions, the locations of ports from East Africa to Indonesia, different wind systems, currents, reefs, headlands and seamarks. The economic and cultural impact of the technological advantage&nbsp;that men like ibn Majid had should not be underestimated, enabling Islam to spread east to India, Malaya, Java, Sumatra and the Philippines, and for Julfar to become for a time the 'centre of the known universe'.<br/><br/>But in 1498 the Portuguese adventurer Vasco da Gama found his way into the Arabian Gulf, and with his superior firepower&nbsp;initiated 500 years of European influence in the region that continued until the late 20th century.&nbsp;Far from being the end of the road for Julfar, the city prospered under the new administration&nbsp;and continued to do so until the mid 18th century, when the ruling Qawasim family&mdash;motivated most probably by shifting navigational channels and sandbars&mdash;relocated their port a couple of miles to the south in what is now Ras al-Khaimah, leaving the old Julfar to gradually decay until&nbsp;the ruins of its mud brick houses became&nbsp;forgotten amongst he sand dunes.</font><br/></font></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></div>

<div><div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-thin " style="padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:left">
<a>
<img src="/web/20171026111746im_/http://www.beyonddubai.net/uploads/2/9/1/0/29102015/710429.jpg?682" alt="Picture" style="width:682;max-width:100%"/>
</a>
<div style="display:block;font-size:90%">Pages from Ibn Majid's masterwork on navigation, the Book of Useful Information</div>
</div></div>

<div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;"><span style="text-decoration:none; font-style:normal; font-weight:400; color:rgb(231, 231, 231); "><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><br/><font size="3"><font size="4"><strong><font size="5">Hili</font></strong><br/>Located just north of Al Ain, the UAE's largest desert oasis town, Hili dates to around 2700 BC, about the same time as the earthworks at Stonehenge were being constructed. Numerous buildings, tombs, and sections of falaj watercourses have been excavated over an area of fifty acres, and is the centrepiece of the UAE's only UNESCO World Heritage site. Unlike most UAE archaeological sites which are poorly signposted if at all and lacking in tourist facilities, an entire park has been built around the Hili site, whose highlight is the magnificently restored&nbsp;Great Tomb, a circular tomb roughly&nbsp;30 ft&nbsp;in diameter made of carefully cut stone blocks and with an elaborately&nbsp;decorated entranceway with two carved oryx and human figures above it.&nbsp;<br/>&nbsp;<br/>Hili represents a snapshot of life during the early Bronze Age period in the Emirates, when people had both mastered the art of extracting copper and turning it into bronze tools and weapons, but had also progressed from a stone age nomadic lifestyle to growing date palms, wheat and barley, for which the art of constructing long irrigation canal or falaj were an essential prerequisite.</font><br/></font></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></div>

<div><div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-thin " style="padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:left">
<a>
<img src="/web/20171026111746im_/http://www.beyonddubai.net/uploads/2/9/1/0/29102015/5199307.jpg?682" alt="Picture" style="width:682;max-width:100%"/>
</a>
<div style="display:block;font-size:90%">Detail from the entrance to the Great Tomb at Hili</div>
</div></div>

<div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;"><span style="text-decoration:none; font-style:normal; font-weight:400; color:rgb(231, 231, 231); "><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><br/><font size="3"><font size="4"><strong><font size="5">Umm al-Nar</font></strong><br/>Bizarrely, the most famous archaeological site in the Emirates, and the one whose discovery&nbsp;initiated much of the interest in unearthing the country's history as well as named an entire period of culture, is one which you cannot visit at all. <br/><br/>Dated to around 2700 to 2000 BC, Umm al-Nar is located on the island of Sas al-Nakheel, just to the east of the city of Abu Dhabi. It was discovered in 1959 and excavated and restored at the behest of Sheikh Zayed, the founder and first President of the UAE. Over fifty large collective tombs have been found at the site which were subsequently recognised as characteristic of the Bronze Age period. <br/><br/>Sas al-Nakheel proved to be a strategic location however, and over the years became home to the UAE's first oil refinery, an oil storage depot, a chlorine plant, a power station, a desalination plant,&nbsp;and a military airbase&mdash;which between them cover almost every square foot of the island. As a result it is no longer permitted to visit the island, which is only a few hundred yards offshore from the main coastal road into the city. So not so much as a lost city these days, as a forbidden one.</font><br/></font></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></div>

<div><div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style="padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:left">
<a>
<img src="/web/20171026111746im_/http://www.beyonddubai.net/uploads/2/9/1/0/29102015/6907737.jpg?693" alt="Picture" style="width:693;max-width:100%"/>
</a>
<div style="display:block;font-size:90%">Umm al-Nar tomb before and after reconstruction. Image credit Abu Dhabi Islands Archaeological Survey, photos by Peter Hellyer</div>
</div></div>

<div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;"><span style="text-decoration:none; font-style:normal; font-weight:400; color:rgb(231, 231, 231); "><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><br/><font size="3"><font size="4"><strong><font size="5">Jebel Barakah</font></strong><br/>Located an hour to the west of Abu Dhabi on the coastal road to Qatar looking out over the southern Gulf, Jebel Barakah isn't really a lost city since there is no actual evidence of continuous habitation, but it is a remarkable site nonetheless due to its age and location.<br/><br/>It is here that a large number of stone tools dated to 106,000 years ago have been found, a time that dates to soon after humans came 'out of Africa' and migrated first into the Arabian peninsula and&nbsp;present-day Yemen, Oman and the UAE, and subsequently into&nbsp;Asia, Europe and hence the rest of the world.<br/><br/>As such the site is very important in establishing man's earliest history in the region. It was from here that they migrated into&nbsp;the fertile valley that is&nbsp;today occupied by the Arabian Gulf, which most likely became a population centre from which groups of humans periodically spread out to new destinations.&nbsp;As such it represents the very earliest stage of the human history of the Emirates.</font><br/></font></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></div>

<div><div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-thin " style="padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:left">
<a>
<img src="/web/20171026111746im_/http://www.beyonddubai.net/uploads/2/9/1/0/29102015/5676413.jpg?680" alt="Picture" style="width:680;max-width:100%"/>
</a>
<div style="display:block;font-size:90%">Jebel Barakah. Image credit: Abu Dhabi Islands Archaeological Survey.</div>
</div></div>

<div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;"><span style="text-decoration:none; font-style:normal; font-weight:400; color:rgb(231, 231, 231); "><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><span style="color: rgb(231, 231, 231); font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; text-decoration: none;"><br/><font size="3"><font size="4"><strong><font size="5">The Lost City of 'Ad</font></strong><br/>Our final lost city is one that is in the true spirit of Arabian lost cities, like a mirage it was once seen, people have even claimed to have been there, but it remains truly lost, somewhere in the vast dunes of the Empty Quarter south of Liwa.<br/><br/>Its story begins during World War II when an RAF pilot flying a routine two hour trip from Salalah in southern Oman to Muscat in a Lockheed Lodestar transport aircraft lost his bearings and found himself deep in the Empty Quarter before emerging near Sharjah, disoriented and almost out of fuel. At one point in his journey, desperate to identify a landmark to put him on the right track,&nbsp;he saw what appeared to be a small town and descended to 500 ft altitude&nbsp;to take a closer look.&nbsp;On closer inspection the 'town' consisted only of a&nbsp;ruins, including several fort-like structures, but most bizarrely was located on top of a flat-topped hill which rose steeply out of the desert,&nbsp;making it a natural fortress.&nbsp;Circling a couple of times he saw no people, and realizing that he could not land he continued on his way.&nbsp;<br/><br/>A few months later Raymond O'Shea, serving at RAF Sharjah, happened to meet the pilot in the mess and heard the story at first hand. Bitten by the 'lost city' bug he and a friend named Schultz decided to spend their next leave period in an attempt to find it. In his&nbsp;memoirs <em>The Sand Kings of Oman</em>, published two years after the war, he recounts how he and Schultz commandeered a truck, and together with a tracker and camels provided by the Sheikh of Ajman set off across the desert to find the mysterious city.<br/><br/>They reach Liwa by truck and&nbsp;then&nbsp;switch to camels to&nbsp;head further into&nbsp;the desert, where the high dunes and soft sand eventually reduces their progress to a crawl. Low on water and supplies they are on the verge of giving up when they spot the flat-topped hill in the distance. Leaving their camels at the base they climb to the summit on foot where they&nbsp;discover&nbsp;the&nbsp;'town' that the pilot had seen, a collection of ruins hidden from below by&nbsp;a natural bowl-shaped depression on the top of the hill.&nbsp;<br/><br/>Speculating that the town&nbsp;was the 'lost city of King 'Ad', or perhaps the home of a&nbsp;lost tribe which had wandered across the desert centuries earlier, O'Shea took a few photographs and went home, suggesting that more qualified archaeologists should investigate further.<br/><br/>Despite&nbsp;being located only 10 or 20 miles south of Liwa and&nbsp;in an area today heavily explored by oil&nbsp;companies, the site has never been found again.&nbsp;Disappointingly the closer one looks into O'Shea's account the more inconsistencies and holes start to appear;&nbsp;his description of his route and the places he passes through&nbsp;don't make sense, villages are not where he says they are, and areas he claim were high dunes and soft sand are in fact flat gravel plains.&nbsp;Likewise the distances he gives would be impossible to cover in the times he claims. <br/><br/>The final proof of the fakery are in his photographs, which&nbsp;he says are of the deserted city but show several Arab women in abayas in the shadows, and furthermore have been recognized to be taken at a spot just a few miles outside of Muscat. Wherever O'Shea and his friend Schultz went in their commandeered truck, it wasn't he lost city of 'Ad.&nbsp;<br/><br/>But, a mystery remains: even though O'Shea's account of his attempt to find the city was just a figment of his imagination, it does not of course invalidate the original story of the lost pilot.&nbsp;Perhaps he was more lost than he thought, and there could still be&nbsp;some ruins on a&nbsp;hill out there in the desert somewhere. After all the Empty Quarter is a big place...</font></font>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<br/></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></div>

<div><div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style="padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:left">
<a>
<img src="/web/20171026111746im_/http://www.beyonddubai.net/uploads/2/9/1/0/29102015/7647079.png?609" alt="Picture" style="width:609;max-width:100%"/>
</a>
<div style="display:block;font-size:90%">Reproduced from The Sand Kings of Oman by Raymond O'Shea, published in 1947. The fictitious 'Lost City of 'Ad' is located just south of Qidan, centre left of the map.</div>
</div></div>
</div>
</div>
